div.p:
from mortal ken: The phrase (meaning ‘hidden from human sight’) is relatively commonplace in English literature. Sources in which SG might have encountered it include Ann Radcliffe’s (1764-1823) ‘Morning on the Sea-Shore’ ll. 23-6 (published in Poems (1801):
O fairy forms so coy to mortal ken,
Your mystic steps to poets only shewn;
O! lead me to the brook, or hollow’d glen,
Retiring far, with winding woods o’ergrown!

towering…AI and MIDI: Le Tour d’Aï (46º 22’ 19” N, 7º 00’ 7” E;
2331m) and the Aiguille du Midi (45º 52’ 43” N, 0º 53’ 14” E; 3842m).
